Annotation.String: This resource defines the record format for a log. It is designed to be used for SEL logs (from IPMI) as well as Event Logs and OEM-specific log formats. The EntryType field indicates the type of log and the resource includes several additional properties dependent on the EntryType.
This resource shall represent the log format for log services in a Redfish implementation.
Some implementations may allow the deletion of individual Log Entries.
This is the severity of the log entry.
The value of this property shall be the severity of the condition resulting in the log entry, as defined in the Status section of the Redfish specificaiton.
The time the log entry was created.
The value of this property shall be the time at which the log entry was created.
This is the type of log entry.

This property shall represent the type of LogEntry. If the resource represents an IPMI SEL log entry, the value shall be SEL. If the resource represents an Event log, the value shall be Event. If the resource represents an OEM log format, the value shall be Oem.
If the EntryType is Oem, this will contain more information about the record format from the Oem.
The value of this property shall represent the OEM specific format of the Entry. This property shall be required if the value of EntryType is Oem.
If the EntryType is SEL, this will have the entry code for the log entry.
This property shall be present if the EntryType value is SEL. These enumerations are the values from tables 42-1 and 42-2 of the IPMI specification.
If the EntryType is SEL, this will have the sensor type that the log entry pertains to.
This property shall be present if the EntryType value is SEL. These enumerations are the values from table 42-3 of the IPMI specification.
This property decodes from EntryType. If the EntryType is SEL, it is the sensor number. If the EntryType is Event, then the count of events. Otherwise, it is OEM specific.
The value of this property shall be the IPMI sensor number if the EntryType is SEL, the count of events if the EntryType is Event, and OEM Specific if EntryType is Oem.
This property decodes from EntryType. If the EntryType is Event, then it is a message string. Otherwise, it is SEL or OEM specific. In most cases, this will be the actual Log Entry.
The value of this property shall be the Message property of the event if the EntryType is Event, the Description if the EntryType is SEL, and OEM Specific if the EntryType is Oem.

This property decodes from EntryType. If the EntryType is Event, then it is a message id. If the EntryType is SEL, then it contains the Event Data. Otherwise, it is OEM specific. This value is only used for registries - for more information, see the specification.

The value of this property shall the MessageId property of the event if the EntryType is Event, the three IPMI Event Data bytes if the EntryType is SEL, and OEM Specific if the EntryType is Oem. The format of this property shall be as defined in the Redfish specification. If representing the three IPMI Event Data bytes, the format should follow the pattern '^0[xX](([a-fA-F]|[0-9]){2}){3}$', where Event Data 1 is the first byte in the string, Event Data 2 is the second byte in the string, and Event Data 3 is the third byte in the string.
The values of this property shall be any arguments for the message.
This contains message arguments to be substituted into the message included or in the message looked up via a registry.
Contains references to other resources that are related to this resource.
The Links property, as described by the Redfish Specification, shall contain references to resources that are related to, but not contained by (subordinate to), this resource.

This is the URI of the resource that caused the log entry.
The value of this property shall be an href that references the resource for which the log is associated.

This value is the identifier used to correlate events that came from the same cause.

The value of this property shall indicate that events are related and shall have the same value in the case where multiple Event messages are produced by the same root cause. Implementations shall use separate values for events with separate root cause. There shall not be ordering of events implied by the value of this property.
